close_symbols: struct lfs_config (lfs->cfg) fields: block_size, read_size, cache_size, read (function pointer)
explanation:
For deciding whether any executed operations in lfs_bd_read constitute dead code (i.e. could be removed without changing program behaviour) the analyzer needs the following additional symbols and definitions:

- lfs_t
  - Required to know layout/semantics of the filesystem state object used throughout the function (especially access to cfg and block_count). Whether certain checks/assignments are no-ops or influence state depends on the fields of this type.

- struct lfs_config (lfs->cfg) fields: block_size, read_size, cache_size, read (function pointer)
  - The function heavily uses these configuration values to decide branch conditions, alignment, and sizes. Understanding their types/ranges and whether cfg->read has side-effects is essential to determine if calls or branches (for example the bypass read path, cache sizing) are removable without changing behaviour.

- lfs_cache_t (fields: block, off, size, buffer)
  - The function reads and writes these fields (pcache and rcache). To know if writing rcache->block/off/size is observable (or redundant) you must know whether these fields are used elsewhere and their semantics (e.g. whether buffer aliasing can occur). Also needed to determine whether pcache/rcache can be null or always non-null.

- lfs->block_count
  - Used in bounds checks and assertions. Knowing its semantics (0 means disabled?), range and whether other code relies on these checks affects whether the checks/returns are meaningful or removable.

- LFS_ERR_CORRUPT
  - The return value on an out-of-range check. To decide if that early return is meaningful (observable) you must know the error code semantics and how callers react.

- LFS_ASSERT macro/definition
  - The code contains LFS_ASSERT(...) calls. Whether those are executed and whether removing them would alter behaviour depends on the macro definition (no-op in release builds vs abort/side-effect in debug). This is central to deciding if the assert statements are dead code.

- lfs_min
  - Used repeatedly to clamp sizes and compute diffs. You need its definition/behaviour (pure/no side-effects) to determine if those calls are essential or could be replaced/removed without changing observable effects.

- lfs_aligndown
  - Used to compute aligned offsets for reads. Its definition/behaviour (pure/no side-effects) and return properties (e.g. can return the same value as input) determine whether the alignment calculations/reads are necessary.

- lfs_alignup
  - Used to compute rcache->size. As with aligndown, knowing its semantics is necessary to decide if the rcache load calculations are meaningful.

- cfg->read implementation/signature/side-effects (and return semantics)
  - The call to lfs->cfg->read(block, off, data, diff) performs I/O and may have side-effects beyond filling the user buffer (e.g. device state, caching, timing). Whether removing or bypassing reads (or removing the read call in certain branches) changes program behaviour depends entirely on its side-effects and error semantics (what return values mean). The analyzer must know whether read is pure (only writes 'data') or has other observable effects.

- memcpy (semantics)
  - memcpy writes the destination buffer. To reason if the in-cache memcpy branches are dead (removable) you must know that they modify 'buffer' and whether equivalent writes would still happen through subsequent reads (and any timing/side-effects implications). Standard semantics needed for that judgement.

- types: lfs_size_t, lfs_block_t, lfs_off_t
  - Precise widths/signedness / overflow behaviour affect guard conditions (off+size overflow), alignment computations and whether certain branches can actually occur. This can make branches effectively impossible (dead) or necessary.

Providing these symbols/definitions lets the next analyst determine which executed operations are observable (affect program state, outputs, timing or side-effects) and which, if any, could be removed without changing program behaviour (i.e. dead code) per the MISRA rule.
